  Claims we have a priori presumptive right to trust testimony absent
  defeating evidence. Challenges Humean reductionism by showing it leads to
  vicious circularity—we need testimony to learn about testimony's
  reliability. Argues most of our knowledge depends essentially on testimony.

  RELEVANCE: Coady's anti-reductionism provides philosophical foundation
  for trusting tradition without requiring each generation to independently
  verify inherited beliefs. His arguments that testimony is epistemically
  basic support view that traditional knowledge can be justified even when
  recipients lack direct evidence. The scale of our dependence on testimony
