  POSITION: Seminal defense of anti-reductionism in testimony epistemology,
  establishing testimony as autonomous knowledge source.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, anti-reductionism, epistemic-sources, High}
}

@article{simion2020testimonial,
  author = {Simion, Mona},
  title = {Testimonial contractarianism: A knowledge-first social epistemology},
  journal = {Noûs},
  year = {2020},
  volume = {55},
  number = {4},
  pages = {783--801},
  doi = {10.1111/nous.12337},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Defends anti-reductionism about testimony through
  "testimonial contractarianism"—the view that speakers and hearers operate
  under implicit social contract whereby speakers are obligated to comply
  with norms governing speech acts (assert only what you know), and hearers
  are entitled to presume compliance. This explains why testimonial
  entitlement is "easy to come by" despite speakers' freedom to lie.
  Knowledge-first approach: norms of assertion are knowledge norms, making
  testimonial default rational.

  RELEVANCE: Simion's social contract framework applies naturally to tradition,
  which involves implicit transgenerational contracts about preserving and
  transmitting knowledge. If traditions operate under norms requiring
  fidelity to inherited wisdom, participants may be rationally entitled to
  trust traditional teachings by default. The knowledge-first approach
  suggests that epistemic evaluation of tradition should focus on whether
  traditional practices reliably transmit knowledge, not merely true belief.

  POSITION: Contemporary defense of anti-reductionism grounded in knowledge-first
  epistemology and social contract theory.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, anti-reductionism, knowledge-first, High}
}

@article{longino2022social,
  author = {Longino, Helen E.},
  title = {What's Social about Social Epistemology?},
  journal = {The Journal of Philosophy},
  year = {2022},
  volume = {119},
  number = {4},
  pages = {169--195},
  doi = {10.5840/jphil2022119413},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Criticizes mainstream social epistemology for adopting
  "thin" conception of sociality that merely adds testimony and disagreement
  to individualistic epistemology. Argues scientific practice reveals "thick"
  sociality where interaction among researchers is central to knowledge-making,
  disagreement and testimony are resources rather than problems, and
  determining what counts as evidence emerges through discursive interactions.
  Challenges individualistic assumptions about cognitive agents and starting
  points for epistemological reflection.

  RELEVANCE: Longino's critique of thin sociality applies to analyses of
  tradition that treat it merely as aggregated individual testimony. Her
  emphasis on thick social processes—where evidence standards and knowledge
  emerge through community interaction—captures how traditions function as
  collective epistemic systems. Traditional practices embody communal
  determinations of what counts as evidence and how to evaluate it, developed
  through generations of discursive interaction. This suggests traditions
  require social-processual rather than individualistic epistemic analysis.

  POSITION: Argues for robustly social epistemology centered on scientific
  practice and collective knowledge production.
  },
  keywords = {social-epistemology, scientific-practice, collective-knowledge, High}
}

@article{palermos2020epistemic,
  author = {Palermos, Spyridon Orestis},
  title = {Epistemic Collaborations: Distributed Cognition and Virtue Reliabilism},
  journal = {Erkenntnis},
  year = {2020},
  volume = {87},
  number = {3},
  pages = {1481--1508},
  doi = {10.1007/s10670-020-00258-9},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Combines virtue reliabilism with distributed cognition
  hypothesis to argue for strong epistemic anti-individualism. Epistemic
  collaborations (research teams, transactive memory systems) produce beliefs
  with positive epistemic standing through mutual interactions of members,
  where this standing is irreducible collective property. Groups themselves
  can be epistemic agents possessing collective cognitive abilities. This
  "distributed virtue reliabilism" shows how collaborative knowledge is
  distinct from knowledge aggregated from individuals.

  RELEVANCE: Palermos's framework directly supports epistemic value of
  tradition understood as distributed cognitive system. Traditional practices
  constitute epistemic collaborations where knowledge emerges from mutual
  interactions across generations, with cognitive labor distributed among
  participants. The collective cognitive abilities embodied in traditions
  (craft knowledge, institutional wisdom) may exceed what any individual
  possesses. Distributed virtue reliabilism provides theoretical foundation
  for claiming traditions can know things no individual member knows.

  POSITION: Defends strong anti-individualism through distributed virtue
  reliabilism, arguing group knowledge is irreducible to individual knowledge.
  },
  keywords = {distributed-cognition, collective-knowledge, virtue-epistemology, High}
}

@article{muller2024transmission,
  author = {Müller, Basil},
  title = {The Transmission of Cumulative Cultural Knowledge—Towards a Social Epistemology of Non-Testimonial Cultural Learning},
  journal = {Social Epistemology},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {39},
  number = {4},
  pages = {496--516},
  doi = {10.1080/02691728.2024.2356588},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Argues that cumulative cultural knowledge (CCK)—knowledge
  acquired through social learning and refined over generations—deserves
  epistemic credit beyond standard testimony accounts. CCK transmission
  involves non-testimonial cultural learning (observation, imitation,
  participation) not captured by testimony-focused epistemology. Agents
  deserve epistemic credit for promoting community's epistemic need for
  efficient, safe CCK transmission. Critiques Greco's knowledge-economy
  framework for excessive focus on testimony; proposes broader account of
  cultural learning.

  RELEVANCE: Müller's focus on cumulative cultural knowledge directly
  addresses tradition's epistemic value. Traditions are paradigm cases of
  CCK—knowledge refined over generations through cultural learning. His
  argument that CCK transmission deserves epistemic credit provides
  philosophical foundation for valuing tradition's role in preserving and
  transmitting knowledge unavailable through individual inquiry. The emphasis
  on non-testimonial learning (learning by doing, apprenticeship) captures
  how much traditional knowledge operates.

  POSITION: Argues for expanded social epistemology beyond testimony to
  accommodate cumulative cultural knowledge transmission.
  },
  keywords = {cultural-learning, cumulative-knowledge, tradition, High}
}

@article{kusch2002testimony,
  author = {Kusch, Martin},
  title = {Testimony and the Value of Knowledge},
  journal = {Episteme},
  year = {2002},
  volume = {1},
  number = {1},
  pages = {39--59},
  doi = {10.3366/epi.2004.1.1.39},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Develops "communitarian value-driven epistemology" drawing
  on Craig's epistemic genealogy and Barnes/Shapin's sociology of knowledge.
  Argues testimony should be understood as collective good underwritten by
  intrinsic values of accuracy and sincerity. Protoknowledge attributions
  function as ascriptions of honor within communities. Defends Craig's
  position against Kvanvig by treating testimony as social institution with
  interrelated epistemic and social values. Knowledge attributions are
  intertwined with attributions of freedom and reliability.

  RELEVANCE: Kusch's communitarian approach illuminates how traditional
  knowledge functions within communities. Treating testimony as collective
  good applies to tradition—traditional knowledge is communal resource
  underwritten by norms of accuracy and sincerity across generations. The
  connection between knowledge attributions and honor/reliability captures
  how traditions confer epistemic authority. His integration of epistemic
  and social values suggests evaluating tradition requires understanding
  both truth-conduciveness and role in constituting community identity.

  POSITION: Defends communitarian, value-driven approach to testimony
  integrating epistemic genealogy and sociology of knowledge.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, communitarian-epistemology, epistemic-value, Medium}
}

@article{levy2019knowledge,
  author = {Levy, Neil and Alfano, Mark},
  title = {Knowledge From Vice: Deeply Social Epistemology},
  journal = {Mind},
  year = {2019},
  volume = {129},
  number = {515},
  pages = {887--915},
  doi = {10.1093/mind/fzz017},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Argues contemporary epistemology's weak anti-individualism
  is inadequate for understanding human knowledge production and transmission.
  Dispositions and norms that are knowledge-conducive in familiar cases
  (individual reasoning, testimony) may not be generally knowledge-conducive.
  Individual-level epistemic vices can be epistemic virtues in common social
  contexts due to distributed cognition and division of cognitive labor.
  Epistemology must become more deeply and pervasively social to capture
  how knowledge actually works.

  RELEVANCE: Levy and Alfano's argument for deeply social epistemology
  challenges individualistic evaluation of tradition. What appears as
  epistemic vice at individual level (uncritical acceptance of inherited
  beliefs) may be epistemic virtue at collective level (preserving hard-won
  knowledge, maintaining cultural stability for knowledge accumulation).
  Their emphasis on division of cognitive labor applies to tradition—
  different generations and roles specialize in different aspects of
  knowledge preservation and application. Suggests evaluating tradition
  requires examining collective epistemic outcomes, not just individual
  rationality.

  POSITION: Defends deeply social epistemology where epistemic evaluation
  must attend to collective processes and distributed cognition.
  },
  keywords = {social-epistemology, distributed-cognition, epistemic-vice, Medium}
}

@article{fricker2006testimony,
  author = {Fricker, Elizabeth},
  title = {Testimony and Epistemic Autonomy},
  journal = {Royal Institute of Philosophy Supplements},
  year = {2006},
  volume = {59},
  pages = {225--250},
  doi = {10.1017/S1358246100009620},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Defends epistemic autonomy ideal against uncritical
  acceptance of testimony. Argues hearers should critically monitor testimony
  for signs of insincerity or incompetence rather than accepting it by
  default. Reductionist position: testimonial justification requires hearer
  to possess evidence of speaker's reliability, either case-specific or
  general inductive evidence. Critical stance preserves epistemic autonomy—
  subjects drawing own conclusions from their evidence. Challenges
  anti-reductionist presumptive right to trust testimony.

  RELEVANCE: Fricker's defense of epistemic autonomy represents key objection
  to uncritical acceptance of tradition. If epistemic autonomy requires
  critically assessing inherited beliefs rather than accepting them by
  default, this challenges Burkean deference to tradition. However, her
  focus on individual autonomy may overlook collective epistemic benefits
  of tradition (distributed cognition, cumulative knowledge). The tension
  between individual epistemic autonomy and collective epistemic achievements
  is central to evaluating tradition's epistemic value.

  POSITION: Defends reductionism and epistemic autonomy against anti-reductionist
  default trust in testimony.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, epistemic-autonomy, reductionism, Medium}
}

@article{dellsen2018epistemic,
  author = {Dellsén, Finnur},
  title = {The epistemic value of expert autonomy},
  journal = {Philosophy and Phenomenological Research},
  year = {2018},
  volume = {100},
  number = {2},
  pages = {344--361},
  doi = {10.1111/PHPR.12550},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Argues for epistemic value of expert autonomy while
  acknowledging social nature of inquiry. Experts in epistemic community
  should evaluate evidence themselves rather than deferring to others.
  Develops notion of "expert acceptance" as appropriate epistemic stance
  for experts. Expert autonomy makes joint testimony more reliable,
  benefiting both laypeople and experts in other fields. Balances Enlightenment
  autonomy ideal with recognition of distributed knowledge and social
  expertise.

  RELEVANCE: Dellsén's framework illuminates division of epistemic labor
  within traditions. While laypeople may appropriately defer to traditional
  wisdom, those charged with maintaining and developing tradition (scholars,
  practitioners, elders) require autonomy to critically evaluate inherited
  knowledge. This suggests tradition's epistemic value depends on maintaining
  appropriate balance: experts exercising autonomy to test and refine
  traditional knowledge while preserving benefits of collective wisdom.
  Pure deference undermines reliability; autonomous expertise within
  tradition enhances it.

  POSITION: Defends epistemic autonomy for experts within social knowledge
  systems, balancing individual and collective epistemology.
  },
  keywords = {epistemic-autonomy, expertise, testimony, Medium}
}

@article{bartha2024shepherd,
  author = {Bartha, David},
  title = {Shepherd's social epistemology: A nonreductive theory of testimony and the question of epistemic autonomy},
  journal = {The Southern Journal of Philosophy},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {62},
  number = {4},
  pages = {583--607},
  doi = {10.1111/sjp.12600},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Examines Mary Shepherd's 19th-century nonreductionist
  account of testimony. Shepherd argues hearers are caused and justified to
  regard testimony as true by default absent undefeated defeaters, without
  requiring positive evidence of speaker reliability. Her commitment to
  epistemic autonomy explains why, despite accepting testimony about events,
  she denies we should base philosophical judgments on others' authority or
  common sense. A priori right to trust testimony about events doesn't
  extend to metaphysical principles.

  RELEVANCE: Shepherd's position offers nuanced view of testimony's
  epistemic role relevant to tradition. Default trust in testimony about
  empirical matters (what happened) may not justify deference on fundamental
  philosophical/metaphysical questions (why things are as they are). Applied
  to tradition: we may be entitled to trust traditional empirical knowledge
  (practices, techniques) while maintaining autonomy on theoretical
  justifications. This distinguishes epistemic value of tradition as
  repository of practical wisdom from problematic deference to tradition
  as philosophical authority.

  POSITION: Historical case study of nonreductionism that preserves
  epistemic autonomy on philosophical matters.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, anti-reductionism, epistemic-autonomy, Medium}
}

@article{obrien2025sympathy,
  author = {O'Brien, Dan},
  title = {Sympathy in Hume's social epistemology},
  journal = {The Southern Journal of Philosophy},
  year = {2025},
  volume = {63},
  number = {1},
  pages = {124--149},
  doi = {10.1111/sjp.12634},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Challenges standard reductionist interpretation of Hume
  on testimony. Argues Hume's epistemology involves two ways of acquiring
  beliefs: probabilistic assessment (causal inference) and sympathetic
  transmission. Sympathy transmits testimonial beliefs acquired uncritically
  from others, providing background against which probabilistic assessment
  operates. Sympathy integrates causal reasoning with socially constructed
  selves and moral lives. As children and adults we imbibe beliefs from
  others through sympathy, not causal inference about testifier reliability.

  RELEVANCE: O'Brien's analysis of sympathy captures non-inferential
  transmission of traditional beliefs. Much traditional knowledge is acquired
  through sympathetic identification with community rather than rational
  assessment of evidence. This suggests tradition operates partly through
  non-rational but epistemically legitimate processes (enculturation,
  habituation). However, raises question whether sympathetically acquired
  traditional beliefs are genuinely justified or merely caused. The
  integration of sympathy with causal reasoning suggests tradition's
  epistemic value lies in providing framework for evidence evaluation, not
  replacing it.

  POSITION: Interprets Hume as recognizing non-inferential sympathetic
  belief transmission alongside evidential reasoning.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, Hume, sympathy, cultural-transmission, Medium}
}

@article{chick2021epistemic,
  author = {Chick, Matthew},
  title = {The Epistemic Value of Testimony},
  journal = {Contemporary Political Theory},
  year = {2021},
  volume = {21},
  number = {1},
  pages = {93--113},
  doi = {10.1057/s41296-022-00548-7},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Develops novel epistemic justification for including
  testimony in deliberative democracy. While some defend testimony on
  grounds of democratic inclusion, this paper argues testimony has intrinsic
  epistemic value: introducing new information, enabling deliberators to
  grasp connections between particular and general, and inviting imaginative
  engagement with others' experiences. These epistemic benefits provide
  reasons for including testimony beyond procedural fairness.

  RELEVANCE: Chick's argument for testimony's epistemic value applies to
  tradition's role in collective decision-making. Traditional narratives and
  testimony introduce information about past consequences of actions, enable
  grasping connections between particular historical cases and general
  principles, and invite imaginative engagement with ancestral experiences.
  This suggests tradition's epistemic value for communities includes enriching
  deliberative resources beyond what present members could generate. However,
  limited to deliberative contexts; doesn't address whether tradition itself
  is epistemically reliable.

  POSITION: Argues testimony has distinctive epistemic value in deliberative
  contexts, not merely procedural value.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, deliberative-democracy, epistemic-value, Medium}
}

@article{giovagnoli2019indirect,
  author = {Giovagnoli, Raffaela},
  title = {"Indirect" Information: The Debate on Testimony in Social Epistemology and Its Role in the Game of "Giving and Asking for Reasons"},
  journal = {Information},
  year = {2019},
  volume = {10},
  number = {3},
  pages = {101},
  doi = {10.3390/INFO10030101},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Analyzes testimony debate (reductionism vs. anti-reductionism,
  communitarian epistemology) through inferentialist lens following Sellars
  and Brandom. Testimony is fundamental shared knowledge source requiring
  dialogical perspective with deontic statuses and attitudes. Reformulates
  "space of reasons" socially—understanding testimony requires examining
  formal structure of "giving and asking for reasons" that establishes
  epistemic entitlements and commitments in communicative practices.

  RELEVANCE: Giovagnoli's inferentialist approach illuminates tradition's
  role in "space of reasons." Traditional beliefs carry deontic commitments—
  inheriting tradition involves undertaking responsibility to preserve and
  transmit knowledge, making oneself answerable to community standards.
  Tradition structures the game of giving and asking for reasons by
  establishing what counts as reason, what requires justification, what can
  be taken for granted. This suggests tradition's epistemic value lies partly
  in constituting normative framework for rational discourse itself.

  POSITION: Analyzes testimony through inferentialist framework emphasizing
  deontic structure of epistemic practices.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, inferentialism, social-epistemology, Medium}
}

@article{hjorland2024social,
  author = {Hjørland, Birger},
  title = {Social Epistemology},
  journal = {Knowledge Organization},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {51},
  number = {3},
  pages = {187--216},
  doi = {10.5771/0943-7444-2024-3-187},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Traces history of "social epistemology" from Shera (1951)
  through Goldman and Fuller traditions. Argues both mainstream traditions
  are problematic as genuine social epistemology. Authentic social epistemology
  is alternative to individualist epistemologies with roots in Hegel, Marx,
  Peirce, and development through Kuhn, pragmatism, hermeneutics, critical
  theory, and feminism. Social epistemology represents alternative to
  positivism. Shera's vision best represents social epistemology, though
  needed alternatives to positivism (developed 1962) to be realized.

  RELEVANCE: Hjørland's historical analysis helps situate tradition within
  social epistemology. The critique of individualism and the connection to
  hermeneutics and historical consciousness (Hegel) align with understanding
  tradition as socially constituted knowledge. His emphasis on alternatives
  to positivism suggests evaluating tradition requires interpretive,
  historically situated epistemology rather than purely naturalistic analysis.
  The connection to Kuhn's paradigms suggests traditions function like
  paradigms—frameworks constituting what counts as knowledge and evidence.

  POSITION: Surveys social epistemology traditions, arguing for robustly
  social alternative to individualistic epistemology.
  },
  keywords = {social-epistemology, intellectual-history, tradition, Low}
}

@article{janvid2021testimony,
  author = {Janvid, Mikael},
  title = {Testimony in African epistemology revisited},
  journal = {South African Journal of Philosophy},
  year = {2021},
  volume = {40},
  number = {3},
  pages = {279--289},
  doi = {10.1080/02580136.2021.1954766},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Investigates Yoruba epistemic practice based on Hallen
  and Sodipo's fieldwork with Yoruba herbalists. Challenges their unduly
  restrictive view of testimony in Yoruba practice. Argues that oral cultures
  like Yoruba can rely on testimony as justification source without
  succumbing to gullibility or uncritical attitude toward tradition. Uses
  recent analytic epistemology to show how oral cultures maintain critical
  standards while depending heavily on testimonial transmission.

  RELEVANCE: Janvid's analysis of oral culture and testimony directly
  addresses tradition in non-Western contexts. Demonstrates that heavy
  dependence on tradition (oral transmission) is compatible with critical
  epistemic standards. Challenges stereotype that traditional societies
  lack epistemic sophistication. Shows how testimony functions in cultures
  where tradition is primary knowledge source. Suggests epistemic evaluation
  of tradition shouldn't assume Western individualism but should recognize
  diverse ways of maintaining testimonial reliability within traditional
  frameworks.

  POSITION: Defends epistemic legitimacy of testimony-based knowledge in
  oral/traditional cultures.
  },
  keywords = {testimony, oral-culture, tradition, African-philosophy, Low}
}

@article{coliva2025wittgenstein,
  author = {Coliva, Annalisa},
  title = {Wittgenstein and Social Epistemology},
  journal = {Cambridge Elements in Epistemology},
  year = {2025},
  publisher = {Cambridge University Press},
  doi = {10.1017/9781009551311},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: First comprehensive study of Wittgenstein's implications
  for social epistemology. Examines his views on common sense and common
  knowledge, testimony and trust, deep disagreements and genealogical
  challenges. Shows how Wittgenstein challenges individualistic epistemology
  that has dominated philosophy since Descartes. Applies Wittgensteinian
  insights to contemporary social epistemology including epistemic injustice
  and framework relativism.

  RELEVANCE: Wittgenstein's emphasis on practices, forms of life, and
  framework propositions illuminates tradition's epistemic status. His
  notion that some beliefs are not justified by evidence but constitute
  framework for evidence evaluation applies to tradition—traditional beliefs
  often function as "hinges" making inquiry possible rather than requiring
  justification themselves. This suggests some traditional knowledge is
  epistemically basic, grounding rather than requiring justification.
  Framework-relative epistemology could explain both tradition's epistemic
  value and limits.

  POSITION: Applies Wittgensteinian framework to social epistemology,
  emphasizing role of practices and frameworks in knowledge.
  },
  keywords = {Wittgenstein, social-epistemology, framework-relativism, Low}
}

@article{averchi2023husserl,
  author = {Averchi, Michele},
  title = {Husserl's Notion of "Secondary Experience" as an Alternative Basis for Social Epistemology},
  journal = {Journal of the British Society for Phenomenology},
  year = {2023},
  volume = {54},
  number = {2},
  pages = {187--202},
  doi = {10.1080/00071773.2023.2185790},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Develops Husserl's notion of "secondary experience" as
  alternative to mainstream characterization of testimony as "transfer of
  belief." Argues testimony is best understood as sharing of experience
  rather than belief transfer. Provides systematic analysis of Husserl's
  Appendix XII (Husserliana 15) and integrates with Cartesian Meditations
  and Experience and Judgment. Claims Husserl's view is superior to majority
  view in contemporary epistemology.

  RELEVANCE: Husserl's "secondary experience" framework offers richer
  understanding of traditional knowledge transmission. Tradition involves
  sharing experiences across generations, not merely transferring propositional
  beliefs. Apprenticeship, ritual participation, and cultural practices
  transmit experiential knowledge that cannot be reduced to testimony about
  propositions. This phenomenological approach captures how traditional
  knowledge includes embodied, practical, and experiential dimensions that
  purely belief-focused epistemology misses. Suggests evaluating tradition
  requires phenomenology of cultural experience.

  POSITION: Phenomenological alternative to standard testimony epistemology
  emphasizing shared experience over belief transfer.
  },
  keywords = {phenomenology, testimony, Husserl, experiential-knowledge, Low}
}

@article{langvatn2024political,
  author = {Langvatn, Silje A.},
  title = {Political legitimacy in Rawls' early and late political liberalism – Two diverging interpretations},
  journal = {Philosophy \& Social Criticism},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {50},
  pages = {1138--1154},
  doi = {10.1177/01914537241263324},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Rawls's liberal principle of legitimacy (LPL) and later idea of legitimacy based on reciprocity (ILBR) are not merely about when specific laws are legitimate, but about civic constraints on reasoning in fundamental political issues. Michelman's proceduralist interpretation correctly emphasizes constitutional democracy's institutional aspects, but misses how LPL and ILBR require citizens to use public reason when exercising power on constitutional essentials, ensuring long-term stability and reasonable justice. The shift to ILBR assigns new significance to actual citizen deliberation and intersubjective reasoning.

  RELEVANCE: Directly addresses how traditions of public reason constitute political legitimacy in constitutional democracies. Shows that democratic traditions are not static inheritance but require ongoing citizen engagement with shared political-moral ideas. Crucial for understanding when tradition-based constitutional constraints are democratically legitimate versus paternalistic impositions. Connects legitimacy to citizens' reflective acceptance of inherited constitutional framework through reasoned deliberation.

  POSITION: Rawlsian political liberalism emphasizing active deliberative engagement with constitutional traditions, against purely procedural interpretations of legitimacy.
  },
  keywords = {political-legitimacy, public-reason, constitutional-democracy, High}
}

@book{bellamy2007political,
  author = {Bellamy, Richard},
  title = {Political Constitutionalism: A Republican Defence of the Constitutionality of Democracy},
  publisher = {Cambridge University Press},
  year = {2007},
  doi = {10.1017/cbo9780511490187},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Democratic mechanisms of elections and majority rule, not judicial review, best uphold rights and rule of law. Drawing on republican tradition, argues that democratic processes themselves—regular elections, party competition, legislative deliberation—provide sufficient constitutional safeguards. Judicial constitutional review is neither necessary nor democratically legitimate; it represents judicial usurpation of popular sovereignty. Political constitutionalism locates constitutional authority in democratic institutions rather than entrenched legal texts enforced by courts.

  RELEVANCE: Exemplifies position that democratic traditions (competitive elections, parliamentary debate) provide legitimacy without requiring entrenched written constitutional traditions enforced by judges. Challenges dominant view that constitutional traditions require judicial guardianship. Essential for project's question of when inherited traditions support versus constrain democratic values—Bellamy argues democratic traditions are self-correcting and don't need extra-democratic constitutional constraints. Shows republican political tradition offers alternative to liberal constitutionalism.

  POSITION: Political constitutionalism and republican tradition; democracy as self-legitimating political practice.
  },
  keywords = {political-constitutionalism, republicanism, constitutional-democracy, High}
}

@article{freeman1990constitutional,
  author = {Freeman, Samuel},
  title = {Constitutional Democracy and the Legitimacy of Judicial Review},
  journal = {Law and Philosophy},
  year = {1990},
  volume = {9},
  number = {4},
  pages = {327--370},
  doi = {10.2307/3504771},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Judicial review can be a legitimate democratic institution if we understand democracy not just as government form but as form of sovereignty grounded in equality, independence, and political jurisdiction of citizens. The social contract tradition (Locke, Rousseau, Kant, Rawls) conceives democracy as based in equal liberties protected by constitutional principles that citizens would rationally accept. Judicial review protects these constitutional essentials by ensuring laws conform to principles all free and equal citizens could accept, thus serving rather than undermining popular sovereignty.

  RELEVANCE: Shows how constitutional traditions rooted in social contract theory can be reconciled with democratic legitimacy through public justification. Argues that tradition of judicial review serves democracy by protecting conditions for equal citizenship rather than constraining democratic will. Important for project's examination of when inherited institutional traditions (like judicial review) are democratically valuable—Freeman argues they preserve rather than threaten democratic values when grounded in principles of equal respect. Connects constitutional tradition to justification all citizens could accept.

  POSITION: Kantian-Rawlsian constitutionalism; judicial review as protecting conditions for democratic equality.
  },
  keywords = {judicial-review, social-contract, constitutional-democracy, High}
}

@article{michelman2015legitimacy,
  author = {Michelman, Frank I.},
  title = {Legitimacy, the Social Turn, and Constitutional Review: What Political Liberalism Suggests},
  journal = {Comparative \& Non-U.S. Constitutional Law eJournal},
  year = {2015},
  doi = {10.5771/2193-7869-2015-3-183},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Political liberalism's conception of legitimacy requires constitutional review because legitimate exercise of political power in constitutional democracy depends on conformity with a constitution that is itself acceptable to free and equal citizens. The "social turn" in constitutional theory—emphasizing constitution as product of actual social practice rather than abstract principle—complements rather than contradicts political liberalism. Constitutional traditions gain legitimacy through ongoing social acceptance and justification to citizens, not merely through historical pedigree.

  RELEVANCE: Bridges Rawlsian political liberalism and constitutional theory, showing how inherited constitutional traditions become legitimate through continued public justification. Essential for understanding how constitutions as traditional frameworks can be democratically legitimate without being merely conservative preservation. Demonstrates that tradition-based constitutional legitimacy requires both historical inheritance and ongoing social validation through public reason. Addresses project's core question of when traditions are valuable by showing legitimacy depends on justifiability to current citizens, not just historical origin.

  POSITION: Rawlsian political liberalism applied to constitutional law; legitimacy through public justification within constitutional framework.
  },
  keywords = {political-liberalism, constitutional-review, legitimacy, High}
}

@article{ferrara2024engaging,
  author = {Ferrara, Alessandro},
  title = {Engaging the later Rawls on legitimacy},
  journal = {Philosophy \& Social Criticism},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {50},
  pages = {1076--1084},
  doi = {10.1177/01914537241263267},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Michelman's interpretation of Rawls's legitimacy conception through "justification by constitution" faces challenges from two innovations in late Rawls: (1) extending reasonable pluralism to a family of liberal political conceptions of justice, not just comprehensive doctrines; and (2) introducing legitimation based on reciprocity criterion alongside liberal principle of legitimacy. These innovations make constitutional justification more complex and potentially less stable than Michelman suggests. The intergenerational dimension of constitutional legitimacy becomes more problematic when legitimating principles themselves are plural and contested.

  RELEVANCE: Advances debate on how constitutional traditions can remain legitimate across time and reasonable disagreement. Shows tensions in grounding legitimacy in inherited constitutional traditions when citizens reasonably disagree not just about comprehensive doctrines but about political principles themselves. Crucial for project's examination of tradition's value—demonstrates that tradition-based legitimacy becomes unstable when the traditions themselves (liberal constitutionalism) fracture into competing interpretations. Raises question whether constitutional traditions can sustain legitimacy amid deepening pluralism.

  POSITION: Critical engagement with Rawlsian political liberalism; skeptical about stability of constitution-based legitimacy under deep pluralism.
  },
  keywords = {political-liberalism, constitutional-legitimacy, reasonable-pluralism, High}
}

@article{michelman2024political,
  author = {Michelman, Frank I.},
  title = {Political liberalism, dualist democracy and the call to constituent power},
  journal = {Philosophy \& Social Criticism},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {50},
  pages = {1419--1431},
  doi = {10.1177/01914537241293372},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Political liberalism's legitimacy conception requires reconciling democratic popular sovereignty with constraints imposed by inherited constitutional regimes. Drawing on H.L.A. Hart's internal/external perspective distinction, argues that citizens must simultaneously adopt internal attitude of bonding to their society's ongoing legal project and external attitude of critical judgment about whether that project is reasonably acceptable. Constitutional traditions gain legitimacy not merely through past constituent power but through this dual perspective—living within tradition while critically evaluating its justifiability to free and equal citizens.

  RELEVANCE: Addresses fundamental tension in tradition-based constitutional legitimacy: how can inherited constitutional constraints be democratically legitimate if current citizens had no say in their creation? Michelman's solution—combining internal commitment to legal tradition with external critical evaluation—provides sophisticated answer to project's question of when traditions are valuable. Shows legitimacy of constitutional traditions depends on citizens' reflective equilibrium between acceptance of inherited framework and reasoned judgment of its justifiability. Essential for understanding democratic value of legal-constitutional traditions.

  POSITION: Rawlsian political liberalism with Hartian jurisprudence; constitutional traditions legitimate through reflexive citizen perspective.
  },
  keywords = {political-liberalism, constituent-power, constitutional-traditions, High}
}

@article{buchanan2002political,
  author = {Buchanan, Allen},
  title = {Political Legitimacy and Democracy},
  journal = {Ethics},
  year = {2002},
  volume = {112},
  number = {4},
  pages = {689--719},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Political legitimacy does not necessarily require democracy. Legitimacy is the right to rule—the moral justification for imposing binding rules and coercing compliance—while democracy is one possible institutional arrangement. An institution is legitimate if it is morally justified in wielding political power; democracy may be instrumentally valuable for achieving legitimacy but is not conceptually necessary for it. Natural duty to support just institutions grounds political obligations, but institutional justice (including procedural fairness) does not require specifically democratic procedures in all contexts.

  RELEVANCE: Challenges assumption that democratic traditions are necessary for legitimate political authority. Important for project because it questions whether specifically democratic traditions have intrinsic value versus instrumental value. If legitimacy can exist without democracy, then democratic traditions' value must be justified on other grounds (justice, rights-protection, etc.) rather than assumed. Separates question of legitimate authority from question of democratic governance, forcing more careful analysis of when democratic traditions specifically are valuable versus when other legitimate institutional traditions might serve better.

  POSITION: Legitimacy as institutional moral justification, conceptually independent from democracy; challenges democracy-centric political philosophy.
  },
  keywords = {political-legitimacy, democracy, institutional-justification, High}
}

@article{christiano2004authority,
  author = {Christiano, Thomas},
  title = {The Authority of Democracy},
  journal = {The Journal of Political Philosophy},
  year = {2004},
  volume = {12},
  number = {3},
  pages = {266--290},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Democracy has intrinsic authority grounded in equal advancement of citizens' interests and public realization of equality. Democratic procedures don't merely produce legitimate outcomes; democracy itself expresses and realizes fundamental equality among citizens. The authority of democratic institutions derives from their embodiment of equal respect and equal concern for all citizens' judgments about justice and common good. Democratic traditions and practices are valuable not instrumentally but because they publicly manifest commitment to equality.

  RELEVANCE: Provides strongest argument for intrinsic value of democratic traditions versus merely instrumental justification. Directly addresses project's question of when traditions are valuable by arguing democratic traditions specifically embody fundamental value of equality. Contrasts with Buchanan's instrumentalism—Christiano argues democratic traditions are valuable because democratic procedures themselves express equal respect, not merely because they produce good outcomes. Shows how specifically democratic traditions (deliberation, voting, etc.) can have inherent value tied to public recognition of equal status.

  POSITION: Intrinsic value of democracy; democratic traditions as public realization of equality.
  },
  keywords = {democratic-authority, political-equality, democracy, Medium}
}

@book{estlund2008democratic,
  author = {Estlund, David},
  title = {Democratic Authority},
  publisher = {Princeton University Press},
  year = {2008},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Democracy's authority derives from epistemic proceduralism—democratic procedures are legitimate because they tend to produce correct or better political decisions than alternative methods while being acceptable to all qualified points of view. Democracy combines epistemic value (truth-tracking) with procedural fairness. Democratic traditions and institutions have authority not merely from agreement or fairness but because they are reasonably regarded as epistemically superior to alternatives (rule by experts, monarchy, etc.) in conditions of reasonable disagreement about who the experts are.

  RELEVANCE: Provides epistemic justification for democratic traditions' value—they track political truth better than alternatives while remaining publicly justifiable. Important for project because it shows democratic traditions aren't merely stable compromises but have cognitive virtues. Addresses question of why specifically democratic traditions matter by arguing they balance epistemic reliability with legitimacy constraints. Shows tension between tradition (inherited procedures) and epistemic responsiveness (updating procedures when better alternatives emerge).

  POSITION: Epistemic proceduralism; democratic traditions as epistemically valuable under fair conditions.
  },
  keywords = {epistemic-democracy, democratic-authority, proceduralism, Medium}
}

@article{greene2017legitimacy,
  author = {Greene, Amanda},
  title = {Legitimacy without Liberalism: A Defense of Max Weber's Standard of Political Legitimacy},
  journal = {Analyse \& Kritik},
  year = {2017},
  volume = {39},
  number = {2},
  pages = {295--324},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Weber's conception of legitimacy as belief in legitimacy (legitimacy beliefs) is more useful for political theory than moralized liberal conceptions. Political legitimacy should be understood sociologically as stable acceptance of authority by subjects, not as moral justification meeting liberal standards. Traditional legitimacy—authority accepted because "it has always been this way"—is genuine form of political legitimacy, not mere stability. Liberal philosophers wrongly dismiss Weberian legitimacy as merely descriptive; legitimacy beliefs themselves have normative significance for political order.

  RELEVANCE: Challenges liberal assumption that traditions need moral justification to confer legitimacy. Provides alternative conception where traditional authority is legitimate simply through stable acceptance, not through meeting reasonability standards. Important for project because it takes seriously the legitimating power of tradition as such, not tradition-as-justified. Raises question whether traditions' value lies in their stability-producing function rather than their justifiability. Shows tension between liberal emphasis on reflective endorsement and conservative/Weberian emphasis on unreflective acceptance of inherited authority.

  POSITION: Weberian descriptive-normative legitimacy; traditional authority as genuine legitimacy form.
  },
  keywords = {legitimacy, tradition, Weber, Medium}
}

@article{trojan2019republican,
  author = {Trojan, C.},
  title = {Republican Auctoritas: Harrington's dual theory of political legitimacy},
  journal = {European Journal of Political Theory},
  year = {2019},
  volume = {20},
  pages = {398--420},
  doi = {10.1177/1474885118806677},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Harrington's republicanism grounds legitimacy in dual requirements: popular power (broad property distribution enabling political participation) and aristocratic authority (auctoritas). Republican legitimacy requires both democratic liberty through property and integration of authority as traditional respect for wisdom and virtue. Liberty alone is insufficient; legitimate republics need hierarchical authority tradition (auctoritas) binding popular power. This dual theory distinguishes Harrington's republicanism from both Hobbesian liberalism and pure democratic populism.

  RELEVANCE: Shows how republican tradition reconciles democratic equality with hierarchical authority traditions. Important for project's question of when traditions are valuable—Harrington argues legitimate polities need both egalitarian traditions (property-based citizenship) and hierarchical traditions (auctoritas, deference to wisdom). Demonstrates that even within republican-democratic theory, certain aristocratic/traditional elements are considered essential for legitimacy. Raises question whether democratic traditions alone suffice or whether they require supplementation by traditions of deference, expertise, or authority.

  POSITION: Republican political theory; legitimacy requiring both popular liberty and traditional authority (auctoritas).
  },
  keywords = {republicanism, political-legitimacy, authority, Medium}
}

@book{jones2020constitutional,
  author = {Jones, Brian Christopher},
  title = {Constitutional Idolatry and Democracy: Challenging the Infatuation with Writtenness},
  publisher = {Edward Elgar},
  year = {2020},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Written constitutions are idolized beyond their democratic value. The fetishization of constitutional texts (constitutional idolatry) undermines democracy by treating inherited documents as sacred rather than as contingent frameworks. Written constitutional traditions encourage passive citizenship and excessive deference to past generations rather than active democratic engagement. The global norm of written constitutionalism is neither necessary nor sufficient for democracy; unwritten constitutional traditions (UK, New Zealand) can be equally or more democratic. Constitutional writtenness has weak connection to democratic quality and may actually impede democratic renewal.

  RELEVANCE: Directly challenges value of constitutional traditions, arguing they often undermine rather than support democracy. Essential for project's critical perspective on when traditions are NOT valuable—Jones argues constitutional textual traditions produce complacency, excessive judicial power, and democratic atrophy. Shows tension between constitutional stability through tradition and democratic responsiveness requiring adaptability. Raises question whether entrenched constitutional traditions necessarily constrain democratic self-governance rather than enabling it, contra defenders of constitutional traditions like Michelman and Ferrara.

  POSITION: Critical of constitutional traditions; argues written constitutional traditions undermine active democratic citizenship.
  },
  keywords = {constitutionalism, democracy, constitutional-idolatry, Medium}
}

@article{gibbs2024foundations,
  author = {Gibbs, Nathan},
  title = {The Foundations of Constitutional Democracy: The Kelsen-Natural Law Controversy},
  journal = {Canadian Journal of Law \& Jurisprudence},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {37},
  pages = {79--107},
  doi = {10.1017/cjlj.2024.3},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Post-WWII debate between natural law theorists (especially Maritain) and Kelsen over constitutional democracy's foundations reveals fundamental question: does constitutional democracy require substantive moral foundation (natural law tradition) or can it rest on relativistic proceduralism? Natural law approach claimed that without foundational moral values grounding constitutional system, democracies would relapse into totalitarianism. Kelsen defended secular, relativistic basis for constitutional democracy, arguing that value pluralism and procedural fairness suffice. The debate raises enduring questions about role of moral traditions and common good in constitutional democracies versus procedural neutrality.

  RELEVANCE: Illuminates tension between constitutional traditions grounded in substantive natural law versus procedural democratic traditions. Essential for project because it shows competing views of what traditions constitutional democracies require—shared moral framework rooted in natural law tradition versus procedural traditions accepting value pluralism. Directly addresses whether constitutional democracies need substantive moral traditions or whether procedural democratic traditions suffice. Connects to broader question of whether traditions must be grounded in truth-claims (natural law) or can rest on pragmatic agreement (Kelsen).

  POSITION: Analysis of natural law versus legal positivism debate; neutral presentation of competing foundations for constitutional democracy.
  },
  keywords = {constitutional-democracy, natural-law, legal-positivism, Medium}
}

@article{chambers2020truth,
  author = {Chambers, Simone},
  title = {Truth, Deliberative Democracy, and the Virtues of Accuracy: Is Fake News Destroying the Public Sphere?},
  journal = {Political Studies},
  year = {2020},
  volume = {69},
  pages = {147--163},
  doi = {10.1177/0032321719890811},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Deliberative democracy requires epistemic virtues—especially Bernard Williams's virtues of accuracy (sincerity and accuracy)—among citizens. While Arendt's analysis of truth and politics is influential, Habermas's truth-tracking conception of deliberative democracy better addresses fake news challenge. Fake news threatens public sphere not just by spreading falsehood but by undermining civic commitment to accuracy virtues. Structural features of public sphere and regulatory frameworks can cultivate accuracy virtues; we see pushback against fake news as citizens become more epistemically responsible. Deliberative democratic traditions depend on shared commitment to truth-seeking and accuracy.

  RELEVANCE: Shows how democratic traditions require epistemic-ethical foundations—specifically traditions of truthfulness and accuracy. Addresses project's question of tradition's value by demonstrating that democratic deliberative traditions break down without shared epistemic virtues. Important for understanding limits of pure proceduralism: even democratic traditions require substantive commitments (accuracy, sincerity) to function. Demonstrates that traditions of reasoned discourse (deliberation, public reason) are valuable because they embody and transmit epistemic virtues necessary for democratic decision-making.

  POSITION: Deliberative democracy requiring epistemic virtues; truth-tracking as essential for legitimate democratic deliberation.
  },
  keywords = {deliberative-democracy, epistemic-virtues, public-sphere, Medium}
}

@article{lafont2020against,
  author = {Lafont, Cristina},
  title = {Against Anti-Democratic Shortcuts: A Few Replies to Critics},
  journal = {Special Issue: Democracy without Shortcuts},
  year = {2020},
  doi = {10.16997/jdd.367},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Democratic legitimacy requires actual citizen participation and deliberation, not merely outcomes that citizens would endorse if they deliberated (hypothetical consent). Rejects "shortcuts" that claim democratic legitimacy through expert deliberation, deliberative minipublics with decision-making power, or judicial review as embodying public reason, when these bypass actual citizen participation. Public reason constraints don't require limiting deliberation to constitutional rights but do require actual public reasoning by citizens themselves. Empowered deliberative minipublics are anti-democratic shortcuts; participatory uses supporting citizen deliberation are valuable.

  RELEVANCE: Challenges tradition-based legitimacy claims that don't involve actual citizen engagement. Important for project because it argues that even valuable traditions (deliberative practices, public reason, constitutional principles) don't legitimate unless citizens actually engage with them. Rejects view that traditions can substitute for democratic participation—Michelman's "exemplar of public reason" courts or Rawlsian idea that constitutional traditions alone suffice. Shows limit of tradition's value: inherited deliberative or constitutional traditions are valuable only when they facilitate rather than replace actual citizen deliberation and decision-making.

  POSITION: Participatory deliberative democracy; against non-participatory legitimacy shortcuts including tradition-based authority.
  },
  keywords = {deliberative-democracy, participation, public-reason, Medium}
}

@article{ingiyimbere2022public,
  author = {Ingiyimbere, Fidèle},
  title = {Public reason under the tree: Rawls and the African palaver},
  journal = {Philosophy \& Social Criticism},
  year = {2022},
  volume = {50},
  pages = {281--298},
  doi = {10.1177/01914537221117254},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: African palaver tradition (deliberation under tree involving community members) shares features with Rawlsian public reason but differs in important ways. Both involve reasoned discussion among free and equal participants about matters of common concern, seeking agreement amid reasonable disagreement. However, palaver tradition emphasizes communal harmony and consensus more than Rawlsian public reason, and may be less individualistic in its assumptions. Comparing Rawls and African deliberative traditions reveals both universal features of legitimate political deliberation and culturally specific elements. Traditions of deliberation take different forms in different cultures but serve similar legitimating functions.

  RELEVANCE: Expands understanding of deliberative traditions beyond Western contexts, showing that diverse cultural traditions can embody similar deliberative ideals. Important for project's question about when traditions are valuable—demonstrates that value lies not in specific Western deliberative forms but in underlying principles (reasoned discussion, equality, seeking agreement). Shows that legitimate political traditions can take culturally specific forms while serving similar democratic functions. Raises question whether political philosophy's emphasis on Western constitutional-deliberative traditions is parochial; perhaps other cultural traditions serve similar legitimating purposes.

  POSITION: Comparative political philosophy; finding convergence between Rawlsian public reason and African deliberative traditions.
  },
  keywords = {public-reason, deliberation, African-philosophy, Low}
}

@article{li2020confucian,
  author = {Li, Zhuoyao},
  title = {Confucian meritocracy, political legitimacy and constitutional democracy},
  journal = {Philosophy \& Social Criticism},
  year = {2020},
  volume = {46},
  pages = {1076--1092},
  doi = {10.1177/0191453720948403},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Rawls's liberal principle of legitimacy can be "deprived of its liberal connotation" by taking constitutional essentials rather than liberal values as legitimation source. This "principle of pluralistic legitimacy" does not rule out Confucian meritocracy (rule by virtuous elites) but requires antiperfectionist state that doesn't impose comprehensive doctrines. Political legitimacy in pluralistic East Asian societies need not require democracy if constitutional framework can be acceptable to citizens holding diverse comprehensive doctrines including Confucianism. Legitimacy derives from constitutional essentials, not specifically from democratic procedures.

  RELEVANCE: Challenges assumption that legitimate political traditions must be democratic, arguing that meritocratic Confucian traditions can be legitimate if constitutionally constrained. Important for project because it questions whether specifically democratic traditions are valuable or whether other traditional forms of governance (meritocracy) can be equally legitimate under pluralism. Shows tension between tradition-based legitimacy claims (Confucian meritocratic tradition) and democratic values. Raises difficult question whether value of political traditions should be assessed by democratic standards or whether diverse legitimate political traditions exist.

  POSITION: Confucian political philosophy; legitimacy through constitutional essentials compatible with non-democratic meritocracy.
  },
  keywords = {Confucianism, meritocracy, political-legitimacy, Low}
}

@article{gowder2019reconstituting,
  author = {Gowder, Paul},
  title = {Reconstituting We the People: Frederick Douglass and Jurgen Habermas in Conversation},
  journal = {Northwestern University Law Review},
  year = {2019},
  volume = {114},
  pages = {335--414},
  doi = {10.31228/osf.io/csr9x},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Constitutional conception of popular sovereignty (Habermasian constitutional patriotism) can resolve countermajoritarian and constituent power problems under conditions of genuine egalitarian inclusion. However, this conception cannot justify states characterized by durable exclusion, such as United States with its treatment of Black Americans. Douglass's constitutional thought offers crucial insight: American constitutional institutions merit conditional attachment based on their latent normative potential despite their actual exclusionary operation. Correct conception for U.S. combines Habermasian constitutional legitimacy with Douglass's recognition of gap between constitutional ideals and exclusionary practice.

  RELEVANCE: Shows limits of constitutional tradition-based legitimacy when traditions are built on exclusion. Essential for project's question of when traditions are valuable versus oppressive—Gowder argues constitutional traditions lack legitimacy when they perpetuate durable exclusion regardless of their procedural features. Demonstrates that value of constitutional traditions depends on actual inclusion, not merely formal equality. Douglass tradition provides critical approach to constitutional traditions: conditional endorsement based on normative potential rather than uncritical acceptance. Shows that evaluating political traditions requires attention to whose voices and interests traditions exclude or marginalize.

  POSITION: Critical constitutional theory combining Habermas and Black radical tradition; legitimacy requires actual not merely formal inclusion.
  },
  keywords = {constitutional-legitimacy, inclusion, Black-political-thought, Low}
}

@book{young1990justice,
  author = {Young, Iris Marion},
  title = {Justice and the Politics of Difference},
  year = {1990},
  publisher = {Princeton University Press},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Young develops a framework of "five faces of oppression" (exploitation, marginalization, powerlessness, cultural imperialism, violence) to analyze structural injustice beyond distributive paradigms. She argues that oppression operates through social structures and cultural meanings, not merely through individual acts or resource distribution. Traditional approaches to justice fail to address these structural forms of domination embedded in social practices and institutions.

  RELEVANCE: Provides the most influential analytical framework for understanding how traditions function as systems of domination. The "five faces" model allows precise diagnosis of different mechanisms through which traditions perpetuate injustice. Crucial for the project's inquiry into harmful traditions: traditions become problematic when they instantiate any of these faces of oppression, particularly through cultural imperialism (imposing dominant group's norms as universal) and systematic violence.

  POSITION: Critical theory approach to social justice; emphasizes group-based structural oppression over individual rights violations.
  },
  keywords = {oppression-theory, structural-injustice, social-groups, High}
}

@book{alexander2006pedagogies,
  author = {Alexander, M. Jacqui},
  title = {Pedagogies of Crossing: Meditations on Feminism, Sexual Politics, Memory, and the Sacred},
  year = {2006},
  publisher = {Duke University Press},
  doi = {10.1515/9780822386988},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Alexander develops transnational feminist theory that critiques both Northern feminism's universalism and the heteronormative regulation of modern state formations, including in postcolonial contexts. She examines how colonial Christianity and neocolonial modernity invented new oppressive "traditions" while criminalizing queer communities in both the US and Caribbean. Transgenerational memory and spiritual practice function as resistance to multiple forms of colonial and patriarchal domination.

  RELEVANCE: Essential for understanding how traditions of oppression are actively constructed by colonial and neocolonial powers, not simply "ancient customs." Demonstrates that critique of harmful traditions must account for how domination creates and invents traditions that serve power. Particularly important for the project's postcolonial dimension: shows how both "Western" and "indigenous" traditions can be heteronormative regulatory mechanisms.

  POSITION: Transnational feminism with postcolonial and queer theory; critiques both Western imperialism and patriarchal nationalisms.
  },
  keywords = {postcolonial-feminism, transnational, queer-theory, High}
}

@article{george2024tradition,
  author = {George, Noel Mariam},
  title = {Are Tradition and Modernity Antagonistic? Ambedkar in and Against the Postcolonial Project},
  journal = {Postcolonial Studies},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {27},
  pages = {248--266},
  doi = {10.1080/13688790.2024.2304472},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: George challenges Ashis Nandy's postcolonial rejection of modernity by examining B.R. Ambedkar's approach to tradition and emancipation. While Nandy sees modernity as colonial domination, Ambedkar synthesized modernity's emancipatory potential (individual liberation) without dismissing communal collective identity. Postcolonial scholarship's conflation of modernity with coloniality creates a problematic choice between oppressive Western modernity and oppressive indigenous traditions, missing possibilities for critical appropriation of both.

  RELEVANCE: Crucial for the project's question of abandoning vs. reforming traditions. Shows that wholesale rejection of either tradition or modernity forecloses emancipatory possibilities. Particularly important for understanding conditions of tradition's value: traditions have value when they can incorporate modernity's emancipatory elements while maintaining cultural continuity, not when they are preserved unchanged or entirely rejected. Ambedkar's caste critique demonstrates tradition-internal grounds for abandoning harmful traditions.

  POSITION: Critical postcolonial theory; argues for selective appropriation of both tradition and modernity against cultural essentialism.
  },
  keywords = {postcolonial-theory, modernity, caste, High}
}

@article{radhakrishnan2025critique,
  author = {Radhakrishnan, Shivani},
  title = {Critique as Coloniality: The Decolonial Challenge to Immanent Critique},
  journal = {Constellations},
  year = {2025},
  doi = {10.1111/1467-8675.12790},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Radhakrishnan challenges Frankfurt School immanent critique methodology from decolonial perspectives (Quijano, Dussel, Lugones, Oyěwùmí). Immanent critique—judging practices by their internal norms—risks: (1) inattentiveness to constitutive exclusions of who counts in the community; (2) placing asymmetrical burdens on marginalized critics to work within frameworks that marginalize them; (3) replicating colonial mechanisms of domination through the practice of critique itself. Critique must attend to power relations governing critique, not just criticized practices.

  RELEVANCE: Provides meta-critical perspective essential for the project: how do we critique harmful traditions without reproducing colonial dynamics? Addresses the methodological problem of when tradition-external critique is legitimate. Shows that even progressive critical methods (Frankfurt School) can perpetuate domination if they assume universal validity of particular cultural frameworks. Essential for navigating universalism vs. relativism debate in the project.

  POSITION: Decolonial epistemology; argues for pluralistic rather than immanent-only methods of critique; centers coloniality of power.
  },
  keywords = {decolonial-theory, critique-method, epistemology, High}
}

@article{ratele2013masculinities,
  author = {Ratele, Kopano},
  title = {Masculinities Without Tradition},
  journal = {Politikon},
  year = {2013},
  volume = {40},
  number = {1},
  pages = {133--156},
  doi = {10.1080/02589346.2013.765680},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Ratele critiques how both traditionalist defenses of hetero-patriarchy and progressive critiques of "traditional masculinity" essentialize and homogenize African tradition. The moment critics invoke "tradition" to reject queer sexualities, they reify a static, tribalized notion of culture. Yet anti-traditionalist critiques also risk cultural imperialism. African traditions have always been dynamic and contested, not monolithic sources of hetero-masculine authority. Recognition of queer desires requires deconstructing false traditionalism without abandoning cultural particularity.

  RELEVANCE: Demonstrates how "tradition" functions as rhetorical weapon to enforce contemporary oppression while claiming ancient authority. Essential for the project's question of distinguishing valuable from harmful traditions: harmful traditions are often recently invented or selectively interpreted to serve current power interests, not genuinely ancient practices. Shows that tradition-critique must be historically informed about what traditions actually were vs. what current authorities claim they were.

  POSITION: Postcolonial queer theory; critiques both traditionalist hetero-patriarchy and Western universalist anti-traditionalism.
  },
  keywords = {masculinity, postcolonial-theory, queer-theory, tradition-invention, Medium}
}

@article{rollo2020silence,
  author = {Rollo, Toby},
  title = {Democratic Silence: Two Forms of Domination in the Social Contract Tradition},
  journal = {Critical Review of International Social and Political Philosophy},
  year = {2020},
  volume = {24},
  number = {3},
  pages = {316--329},
  doi = {10.1080/13698230.2020.1796330},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Rollo identifies how liberal social contract tradition contains "domination contracts" excluding those deemed incapable of speech and reason (particularly children and people with intellectual disabilities). There are two forms: (1) contingent domination contracts (potentially disputed by proving speech/reason capacity—how women and racialized peoples gained inclusion); (2) structural domination contracts (cannot be resolved for those deemed permanently "silent"). The liberal veneration of voice is itself an exclusionary tradition requiring reconceptualization of democratic inclusion.

  RELEVANCE: Exposes how core liberal-democratic traditions embed exclusionary domination while claiming universality. Crucial for the project's question of harmful traditions: some of philosophy's most "progressive" traditions (social contract theory, democratic voice) contain exclusionary mechanisms. Challenges simple progressive/traditional binary. Shows conditions for abandoning traditions: when their central concepts (voice as prerequisite for inclusion) structurally exclude legitimate participants.

  POSITION: Radical democratic theory; critiques liberal tradition from disability and childhood studies perspectives.
  },
  keywords = {social-contract, domination, exclusion, tradition-critique, Medium}
}

@article{vedder2023gendered,
  author = {Vedder, Ophelia},
  title = {Eliminating the Gendered Division of Labor: The Argument from Primary Goods},
  journal = {European Journal of Political Theory},
  year = {2023},
  volume = {24},
  number = {2},
  pages = {335--356},
  doi = {10.1177/14748851231200147},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Vedder argues that Rawls's political liberalism (not just his earlier justice as fairness) provides resources for feminist critique of gendered division of labor. The gendered division of labor distributes primary goods (resources all citizens need as citizens) unfairly to women. She advocates for "Gender Egalitarian Daddy Quota" parental leave policy on grounds that fair distribution of primary goods requires eliminating gendered care traditions. This shows political liberalism can ground feminist transformation without relying on comprehensive doctrines.

  RELEVANCE: Demonstrates how liberal political tradition's own principles can ground critique and transformation of gendered traditions, answering Okin's worry about political liberalism's feminist potential. Relevant to project's question of tradition-reform vs. abandonment: deeply entrenched gendered care traditions can be transformed through policy that realigns incentives and opportunities. Shows conditions under which traditions should be abandoned: when they violate fair distribution of social primary goods necessary for citizenship.

  POSITION: Political liberal feminism; uses Rawlsian framework for gender justice without relying on comprehensive feminism.
  },
  keywords = {feminist-critique, Rawls, gender-justice, tradition-reform, Medium}
}

@article{earp2016fgm,
  author = {Earp, Brian D.},
  title = {Between Moral Relativism and Moral Hypocrisy: Reframing the Debate on 'FGM'},
  journal = {Kennedy Institute of Ethics Journal},
  year = {2016},
  volume = {26},
